 BY MAYOWA SAMUEL The Nigerian Baptist Convention has expressed sadness over the death of a former governor of Oyo State, Adebayo Alao-Akala. Spokesman for the NBC, Eben Durodola, disclosed this in a condolence message he signed and sent to The Point on Thursday. In the statement titled: “Condolence Message on Late Chief Alao Akala, a former governor of Oyo State,” Durodola stated that the news “came as a shock and devastation to the Nigerian Baptist Convention and the All African Baptist Fellowship families.” He described the late Akala’s as “a humble, generous, caring, influential, God-fearing man and an administrator of excellence.” “He lived a fulfilled relational life and achieved much in the areas of politics, charity, personal influence, missions, and helping others. “He was a practical ‘Samaritan’ of our generation. Late Chief Alao-Akala will be remembered for his doggedness and the zeal he exhibited toward the spread and expansion of the gospel of Jesus Christ, during his lifetime.” Noting that Akala “assisted many people to rise in life and was well-loved by his people and Nigeria at large,” Durodola added that “the Nigerian Baptist Convention will miss a great gem, philanthropist, and a very important personality.” He added that the President of the NBC, Israel Akanji and the Baptist family in Africa, commiserate with the Oyo State governor, Seyi Makinde, the people of Ogbomoso and the entire country. He prayed that God consoles the family and everybody he left behind. 